[{"sha":"569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU/GPU] Fix BF16 conversion/reduce-precision for NaNs with weird payloads

EmitReducePrecisionIR is used for two purposes:
 - kReducePrecision
 - kConvert from F32 -> BF16

The kConvert case takes the result of EmitReducePrecisionIR and shifts it right by 16.
If the F32 was a NaN encoded with a payload only in the low bits, the shift would erase the payload turning the NaN into an infinity.

In this case, we force a NaN payload by setting the qNaN bit.

The kReducePrecision wants the NaN back unchanged.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383745625
Change-Id: I76a2aeff51d4c37127faf9f9fc51237208709911","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3"}]

[{"sha":"6bd7c7d251719bf6d9894e2fb4b64a208e56d70e","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Fix fused convolutions with cudnn frontend.

Before this patch, fused bias-activation convolutions has two bugs when the
cudnn frontend API is enabled.

 - While autotuning, we always used 0 bytes of scratch memory for each
   algorithm, even if the algorithm called for more than that.  As a result,
   most algorithms failed.

 - After autotuning, we wouldn't call FusedConvolveWithExecutionPlan.  Instead,
   we'd always call FusedConvolveWithAlgorithm.  As a result, even if we had a
   good conv plan from autotuning, we wouldn't use it; instead, we'd use the
   default conv algorithm.

I verified by code inspection that the other kinds of convolutions don't have
this same bug.

the setting from the external environment. However, "kumactl install"

explictly. Update the remaining uses so that "kumactl install" always
targets the correct test cluster.

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed. The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Signed-off-by: Daniele Rondina <geaaru@sabayonlinux.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/73aef6edfe5ae533f9cf547f924c98a9b0f7be59"},{"sha":"d92739713c633c155c0f3d8065c8278b1d8a44e7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"seccomp.Syscall: embed runtime-spec Syscall type

This makes the type better reflect the difference with the "runtime" profile;
our local type is used to generate a runtime-spec seccomp profile and extends
the runtime-spec type with additional fields; adding a "Name" field for backward
compatibility with older JSON representations, additional "Comment" metadata,
and conditional rules ("Includes", "Excludes") used during generation to adjust
the profile based on the container (capabilities) and host's (architecture, kernel)
configuration.

This change introduces one change in the type; the "runtime-spec" type uses a
`[]LinuxSeccompArg` for the `Args` field, whereas the local type used pointers;
`[]*LinuxSeccompArg`.

In addition, the runtime-spec Syscall type brings a new `ErrnoRet` field, allowing
the profile to specify the errno code returned for the syscall, which allows
changing the default EPERM for specific syscalls.

used, and marked optional / legacy in the OCI distribution-spec:

> Because of the origins this specification, the client MAY encounter

> `Docker-Distribution-API-Version`. These headers are OPTIONAL and
> clients SHOULD NOT depend on them.

handle concurrent operations causing 2 issues:
1) crash from nil pointer exception
2) not proper handling of conflicting configuration

The test with the original code has a low failure frequency
to confirm the fix I had to add a time.Sleep in the body of the
CreateNetwork so to have a 100% failure

- Added remainingReapTime field in the table event.
  Wihtout it a node that did not have a state for the element
  was marking the element for deletion setting the max reapTime.
  This was creating the possibility to keep the entry being resync
  between nodes forever avoding the purpose of the reap time
  itself.

- On broadcast of the table event the node owner was rewritten
  with the local node name, this was not correct because the owner
  should continue to remain the original one of the message

Signed-off-by: Flavio Crisciani <flavio.crisciani@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eliaskoromilas/moby/commits/2d2a2bc56810e9b1aa97a920fe488303cf775bf2"},{"sha":"053a534ab10b652c90700dd9b449eaf9d01aaf0c","author":{"name":"Flavio Crisciani","email":"59eae1aa696b1b39cd87a38bdba3f0b2630647f9@docker.com"},"message":"Changed ReapTable logic

- Changed the loop per network. Previous implementation was taking a
  ReadLock to update the reapTime but now with the residualReapTime
  also the bulkSync is using the same ReadLock creating possible
  issues in concurrent read and update of the value.
  The new logic fetches the list of networks and proceed to the
  cleanup network by network locking the database and releasing it
  after each network. This should ensure a fair locking avoiding
  to keep the database blocked for too much time.

  Note: The ticker does not guarantee that the reap logic runs
  precisely every reapTimePeriod, actually documentation says that
  if the routine is too long will skip ticks. In case of slowdown
  of the process itself it is possible that the lifetime of the
  deleted entries increases, it still should not be a huge problem
  because now the residual reaptime is propagated among all the nodes
  a slower node will let the deleted entry being repropagate multiple
  times but the state will still remain consistent.

Separate the hostname from the node identifier. All the messages
that are exchanged on the network are containing a nodeName field
that today was hostname-uniqueid. Now being encoded as strings in
the protobuf without any length restriction they plays a role
on the effieciency of protocol itself. If the hostname is very long
the overhead will increase and will degradate the performance of
the database itself that each single cycle by default allows 1400
bytes payload

Previously the bitseq alloc was allocating the first available bit from the
begining of the sequence. With this commit the bitseq alloc will proceed
from the current allocation. This change will affect the way ipam and vni
allocation is done currently. The ip allocation will be done sequentially
from the previous allocation as opposed to the first available IP.

[{"sha":"569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU/GPU] Fix BF16 conversion/reduce-precision for NaNs with weird payloads

EmitReducePrecisionIR is used for two purposes:
 - kReducePrecision
 - kConvert from F32 -> BF16

The kConvert case takes the result of EmitReducePrecisionIR and shifts it right by 16.
If the F32 was a NaN encoded with a payload only in the low bits, the shift would erase the payload turning the NaN into an infinity.

In this case, we force a NaN payload by setting the qNaN bit.

The kReducePrecision wants the NaN back unchanged.

Signed-off-by: Matt Morrison <3241034+Emdot@users.noreply.github.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/moby/commits/ff1d9a3ec52e559443c7d36561c903755e57fa7d"},{"sha":"d92739713c633c155c0f3d8065c8278b1d8a44e7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"seccomp.Syscall: embed runtime-spec Syscall type

This makes the type better reflect the difference with the "runtime" profile;
our local type is used to generate a runtime-spec seccomp profile and extends
the runtime-spec type with additional fields; adding a "Name" field for backward
compatibility with older JSON representations, additional "Comment" metadata,
and conditional rules ("Includes", "Excludes") used during generation to adjust
the profile based on the container (capabilities) and host's (architecture, kernel)
configuration.

This change introduces one change in the type; the "runtime-spec" type uses a
`[]LinuxSeccompArg` for the `Args` field, whereas the local type used pointers;
`[]*LinuxSeccompArg`.

In addition, the runtime-spec Syscall type brings a new `ErrnoRet` field, allowing
the profile to specify the errno code returned for the syscall, which allows
changing the default EPERM for specific syscalls.

[{"sha":"569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU/GPU] Fix BF16 conversion/reduce-precision for NaNs with weird payloads

EmitReducePrecisionIR is used for two purposes:
 - kReducePrecision
 - kConvert from F32 -> BF16

The kConvert case takes the result of EmitReducePrecisionIR and shifts it right by 16.
If the F32 was a NaN encoded with a payload only in the low bits, the shift would erase the payload turning the NaN into an infinity.

In this case, we force a NaN payload by setting the qNaN bit.

The kReducePrecision wants the NaN back unchanged.

With this CL, we can enable GPU memory oversubscription via env flags.
For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383728665
Change-Id: Ie8670ea7a3c1ad5851d93ef70b57a822d2d3bd06","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/24e4c8ec69406b56f900875685aaa939959770f7"},{"sha":"6bd7c7d251719bf6d9894e2fb4b64a208e56d70e","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Fix fused convolutions with cudnn frontend.

Before this patch, fused bias-activation convolutions has two bugs when the
cudnn frontend API is enabled.

 - While autotuning, we always used 0 bytes of scratch memory for each
   algorithm, even if the algorithm called for more than that.  As a result,
   most algorithms failed.

 - After autotuning, we wouldn't call FusedConvolveWithExecutionPlan.  Instead,
   we'd always call FusedConvolveWithAlgorithm.  As a result, even if we had a
   good conv plan from autotuning, we wouldn't use it; instead, we'd use the
   default conv algorithm.

I verified by code inspection that the other kinds of convolutions don't have
this same bug.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383739555
Change-Id: I962b1ac39ef7c4aa59ebdd2a151335de6e32702f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/6381dad71d870a2726644fb422a97a97ea4b677c"},{"sha":"569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU/GPU] Fix BF16 conversion/reduce-precision for NaNs with weird payloads

EmitReducePrecisionIR is used for two purposes:
 - kReducePrecision
 - kConvert from F32 -> BF16

The kConvert case takes the result of EmitReducePrecisionIR and shifts it right by 16.
If the F32 was a NaN encoded with a payload only in the low bits, the shift would erase the payload turning the NaN into an infinity.

In this case, we force a NaN payload by setting the qNaN bit.

The kReducePrecision wants the NaN back unchanged.

Previously we would get an error along the lines of

NotFoundError: Resource localhost/hash_table_6d5754e2-c5bd-4c7f-8f99-5aa8782dd5a8/ResourceBase does not exist.

Now the error looks like

FailedPreconditionError: Serialization error while trying to register a dataset with tf.data service. The dataset may depend on a resource located on a different device. To address this, call `register_dataset` from the device with the resource, then use `from_dataset_id` to create per-device datasets. Original error: Invalid argument: Trying to access resource hash_table_8945247c-dee3-4c71-a49b-1d9d8aa5f13c located in device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0 from device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:1

To get the information about which device the resource is being accessed from, this CL plumbs the OpKernelContext through the SerializationContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383728665
Change-Id: Ie8670ea7a3c1ad5851d93ef70b57a822d2d3bd06","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/24e4c8ec69406b56f900875685aaa939959770f7"},{"sha":"6bd7c7d251719bf6d9894e2fb4b64a208e56d70e","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Fix fused convolutions with cudnn frontend.

Before this patch, fused bias-activation convolutions has two bugs when the
cudnn frontend API is enabled.

 - While autotuning, we always used 0 bytes of scratch memory for each
   algorithm, even if the algorithm called for more than that.  As a result,
   most algorithms failed.

 - After autotuning, we wouldn't call FusedConvolveWithExecutionPlan.  Instead,
   we'd always call FusedConvolveWithAlgorithm.  As a result, even if we had a
   good conv plan from autotuning, we wouldn't use it; instead, we'd use the
   default conv algorithm.

I verified by code inspection that the other kinds of convolutions don't have
this same bug.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 383739555
Change-Id: I962b1ac39ef7c4aa59ebdd2a151335de6e32702f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/6381dad71d870a2726644fb422a97a97ea4b677c"},{"sha":"569037f8a620f79ef87056e1046e42356a0ea5e3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU/GPU] Fix BF16 conversion/reduce-precision for NaNs with weird payloads

EmitReducePrecisionIR is used for two purposes:
 - kReducePrecision
 - kConvert from F32 -> BF16

The kConvert case takes the result of EmitReducePrecisionIR and shifts it right by 16.
If the F32 was a NaN encoded with a payload only in the low bits, the shift would erase the payload turning the NaN into an infinity.

In this case, we force a NaN payload by setting the qNaN bit.

The kReducePrecision wants the NaN back unchanged.

[{"sha":"8ffd110da5da70096f4fef635fa8ce7611432346","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Feed input tensors only if shape inference requires constant input

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed. The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Also moved canonicalization tests into a separate file, while adding a new test for quant_raw_data op.

Change-Id: Ia62563b1677b78929b690357a6fa21fd7e85f331","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/2d0c38e8d7958b311e881537cc912b0c5c14d5cd"},{"sha":"8ffd110da5da70096f4fef635fa8ce7611432346","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Feed input tensors only if shape inference requires constant input

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

[{"sha":"e074afc4663247f8400f73bcf61547bf10b030d2","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Add canonicalization pattern for tfr.quant_raw_data op

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed. The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Also moved canonicalization tests into a separate file, while adding a new test for quant_raw_data op.

[{"sha":"2fbbbedda8bd39372448ebd5cf19a40365f1f19f","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[PJRT] Allow GPU memory oversubscription when unified memory is enabled.

With this CL, we can enable GPU memory oversubscription via env flags.
For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

Previously we would get an error along the lines of

NotFoundError: Resource localhost/hash_table_6d5754e2-c5bd-4c7f-8f99-5aa8782dd5a8/ResourceBase does not exist.

Now the error looks like

FailedPreconditionError: Serialization error while trying to register a dataset with tf.data service. The dataset may depend on a resource located on a different device. To address this, call `register_dataset` from the device with the resource, then use `from_dataset_id` to create per-device datasets. Original error: Invalid argument: Trying to access resource hash_table_8945247c-dee3-4c71-a49b-1d9d8aa5f13c located in device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0 from device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:1

To get the information about which device the resource is being accessed from, this CL plumbs the OpKernelContext through the SerializationContext.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,

currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

[{"sha":"d92739713c633c155c0f3d8065c8278b1d8a44e7","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"seccomp.Syscall: embed runtime-spec Syscall type

This makes the type better reflect the difference with the "runtime" profile;
our local type is used to generate a runtime-spec seccomp profile and extends
the runtime-spec type with additional fields; adding a "Name" field for backward
compatibility with older JSON representations, additional "Comment" metadata,
and conditional rules ("Includes", "Excludes") used during generation to adjust
the profile based on the container (capabilities) and host's (architecture, kernel)
configuration.

This change introduces one change in the type; the "runtime-spec" type uses a
`[]LinuxSeccompArg` for the `Args` field, whereas the local type used pointers;
`[]*LinuxSeccompArg`.

In addition, the runtime-spec Syscall type brings a new `ErrnoRet` field, allowing
the profile to specify the errno code returned for the syscall, which allows
changing the default EPERM for specific syscalls.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/d92739713c633c155c0f3d8065c8278b1d8a44e7"},{"sha":"c7cd1b9436ac381747a5c52dddac5a66f97c61f8","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"profiles/seccomp.Syscall: use pointers and omitempty

For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed.
